description:
In 1888, a recording was made of Gladstone's voice on a phonograph cylinder and sent to Thomas Edison. This is a section of the text he read:

The request that you have done me the honour to make - to receive the record of my voice - is one that I cheerfully comply with so far as it lies in my power, though I lament to say that the voice which I transmit to you is only the relic of an organ the employment of which has been overstrained. Yet I offer to you as much as I possess and so much as old age has left me, with the utmost satisfaction, as being, at least, a testimony to the instruction and delight that I have received from your marvellous invention. As to the future consequences, it is impossible to anticipate them. All I see is that wonders upon wonders are opening before us.

I found it here: http://kottke.org/10/08/gladstones-voice
title: William Gladstone for Thomas Edison

Ihr feiert den achten Geburtstag, ein Alter, in dem sonst kaum jemandem eine Laudatio zuteil wird. In acht Jahren habt Ihr aber einiges erreicht, was Anlass zu einer wohlwollenden Rede gibt â€“ und sei es nur, dass Ihr nicht so adipÃ¶s seid, wie Eure kleine Schwester Facebook. Sie ist wohl auch gar nicht Eure Schwester ist, nicht mal eine Stiefschwester, sondern eine Ausgeburt der dunklen Seite, die die RealitÃ¤t abschaffen will.

Ihr seid die "letzte Bastion der Wirklichkeit". Das gallische Dorf also, das sich dem Verlust der Wirklichkeit entgegen stemmt, manchmal mit Zaubertrank, denn Zauber gehÃ¶rt eindeutig zur Wirklichkeit, und Zauber ist es, der den Buchhaltern der PseudorealitÃ¤t Angst macht.

Was ist Wirklichkeit? Der kleinste gemeinsame Nenner, auf den sich mehr oder weniger kranke Gehirne verstÃ¤ndigen? Ein Land in dessen Sprache jeder Satz mit Euro oder Dollar endet? Ein Ort, wo Freude "Wachstum" genannt wird und wo kollektive Fettsucht herrscht?

Ich wÃ¼nsche Euch, dass Ihr groÃŸ und nicht fett werdet und dass Ihr die Wirklichkeit auch weiterhin mit aller Kraft verteidigt und Euch weder vor der groÃŸen Leere noch vor der groÃŸen Ordnung fÃ¼rchtet und schon gar nicht vor dem groÃŸen Chaos, denn das ist vielleicht Euer wichtigster VerbÃ¼ndeter auf der Wanderung durch das mit viel Neonlicht verdunkelte Tal. I had this brother, he was thin and kind

I was at the pier
Cold and broke
Up came this man
Offered me a smoke

He said my friend
You're struggling through the day
Do you know how grand they live in St Tropez

He said I'll give you jewels
I'll make you rich
You'll just tell me what you know
About the Fritz

We'll go to St Tropez
Fuck yeah
Where the cops don't ask you questions
Whenever someone dies
And the whores are wrapped in diamonds
And the thieves wear thousand dollar ties

To sunny St Tropez 
Fuck yeah
Where the toilets are made of gold
They put champagne on your fries
And the whores are wrapped in diamonds
And the thieves wear thousand dollar ties

But I denounced him
To the Feds
I hoped they'd give me
Some money for his head

But the Feds took precautions
Arrested me as well
And sent me off to Cuba
To this Twenty five foot cell

Now there's only one thing
That gets me through the day
I know one day I'll make it
To sunny St Tropez

description:
One night in an echoey venue
Full of artists I canâ€™t abide
Talking fluff and collecting opinions
Freezing dogs in formaldehyde

You are wearing wool and we argue
My ears prick up and your eyes are wide
You say some awesome shit and I like you
As our thick black rims collide

Some things
Are better left undone
Some songs
Are better left unsung
Some dreams
Are neither right nor wrong
Sometimes
I think that you're the one
[repeat]

[howling bridge]

Your hair is bobbed and your neck is perfection
Your skirt puffs out and your nylon sheens
You tilt your head at an excellent angle
I take you out coz youâ€™re from my dreams

We find a cafe on broadway market
We have a dish that is mostly greens
You look me right in the eye and you tell me
Just what uncle Wilhelm means

[chorus]

Now we're out and we look like a couple
Our lives are short but our hearts are free
The days are cold but our warmth is relentless
You make the me that I want to be

No rush, now it feels like forever
The past is just a lost memory
It's not the end, it's the way that we get there
No need for vertical strategy

[chorus]

One night and we're out past our bedtime
I hold your hand and you smile at me
My time with you is so utterly precious
The perfect romantic comedy

We hold ourselves in mechanical tension
Your body smiles and your face just beams 
Itâ€™s not the fuck, itâ€™s the loss of the ego
Somehow our real life intervenes
title: Somethings

description:
Back in early 2001, myself and a couple of friends were hanging around a cockney spiritual guru called Dave Oshana.  He had mad cold reading skills, and a wicked sense of humour.  Surrounded by Sannyasin seekers, enlightenment was serious business, which created the most electric comic tension.  We were baked off our faces back then, by which I mean 20 spliffs a day baked; the whole thing was hysterical, and true, and we grocked it in the most profound way.

But Dave had problems reaching his less cosmic students, who wanted to become enlightened by telephoning him at night or falling asleep in a room with him.  So a friend of his came to the rescue, and created a song through which the enlightenment could flow.  A snippet of that song is available below, but it somehow wasn't working.  What Dave needed was something altogether more powerful.

I called my contribution "Enlightenment by Bugle", and if it doesn't enlighten the absolute fuck out of you, I don't know what will.

Inspired by http://www.enlightenment-now.com/audio/oshana-enlightenment-consciousness-inevitable-demo.mp3
title: Enlightenment by bugle

A companion, a marker, a proper windbreaker! Turn up your headphones, step into your own imaginary limelight, and push things forward.

description:
I might come across as a fun-loving, carefree kind of guy and I live in what is supposed to be one of the most gender equal countrys in the world. But this past year has yet again blatantly proven that we still have a very long way to go before we as a society can call ourselves united and equal. 

As a white male today who claims artistic space, I feel that itÂ´s my responsibility to stand up and ask my male peers to join me in this fight against sexism and inherited power structures of toxic male norms.

This is a track that has been a staple as the grand finale of my live set for some time and IÂ´m very excited to share it with you as a free download thru my Bandcamp page.
title: I Stand Up And Say, Toxic Masculinity Has Got To Go Away

description:
Cissi Moon changed my life! It was in a now refurbished part of Stockholm in a futuristic cafe/club called Holger that i had my first encounter with loudly played club music. The night was called dB and we lined up with our fake IDs every Saturday to hear Cissi Moon spin Drum & Bass records and let the bass engulf our beings.

At the time the art of making electronic music was totally alien to me, I could not for the life of me work out how to ever make music that carried the same emotional and physical impact as I felt on that dance floor .
I have spent the last 17 years or so trying to get back to that state of being at one and completely lost with the music. 

This record concludes a trilogy of EPs by Peder Mannerfelt on his eponymously named label. What comes next is everything and beyond.

description:
Peder Mannerfeltâ€™s release for Archives IntÃ©rieures takes us back to Belgian Congo in the 1930's.

This adventurous album finds its roots in a very obscure 78 rpm record, put together by Belgian filmmaker Armand Denis, who was one of the first Europeans to capture the incredible sounds of Central Congo. These recordings were published in 1950 as The Belgian Congo Records.

Mannerfelt is an avid collector of African tribal music. When he came across this record he was immediately intrigued by the complexity and rendition of these recordings of Congolese music. His initial idea was to use the original album as a sample source, but this concept was quickly abandoned and Peder decided to recreate the album using only synthesizers.

The Swedish Congo Record is first and foremost a thrilling, refreshing album. However, it is also an unintentional critique on a dark passage in Belgian history. The colonial times are marked by a violent, shameless exploration and exploitation of resources and people. On a humanitarian, political and social level a deep scar was left behind by this period of Western European Colonialism. Still now Western economic interests continue to influence the fate of central Africa. Simply sampling the original album could be seen as another way of colonising or disrespectful appropriation. However, by re-sculpting the album, reshaping its original musicality into a wild electronic universe of his own, Mannerfelt pays tribute to the traditional and folkloric meaning of the dances.

The nature of this tribal music pushed Mannerfelt to further explore his unique sense of rhythm heâ€™s known for with Roll The Dice as well as with his solo work. The Swedish Congo Record also bears his signature way of combining skilful productions with a touch of humour, which results in a multi-faceted, daring album.

description: Following on from her highly acclaimed 'Ett' lp on Editions Mego Klara Lewis presents 4 new works which further her signature explorations of field recordings, electronics, rhythm, sound and atmosphere. Here Lewis exemplifies her uncanny ability to harness the world outside in order to reconstruct and re-present this as amorphous musical matter.Â  These 4 new tracks exude a certain ambiguity where standard signposts such as rhythm, ambience, texture, light and dark remain as elusive as they are present. Whilst bypassing passive or photographic representation of the source material these works withhold a strong emotional quality resulting in a confident and at times brutal musical manifestation.Â  As suggested by the title, Msuic resides in a zone at once familiar and slightly off kilter, a world of Lewis' devising in which the listener is warmly encouraged to enter and explore. Msuic is another superb collection of music as fantastic matter.Â

description:
Great music reaches further than your ears can register. Listening to a recent recording from Peder Mannerfelt is like listening to a complete work flow. The superb music created inside of Peder Mannerfelts Villa NellcÃ´te. 
The opening track of EP2 "Rhythm Inflection" is similar to a heartbeat, rebuilt using a parade of machines, iceÂ­ cold biting sounds that implies a climax that never materialize. 
Repetitive thuds are the wrecking ball of "Technology As Apathy" while saw waves continuously crunch until your ear are obliterated on "Failed Grammarâ€. "Titled" is the centerpiece, however. Its sonic gears grind into hollowedÂ­ out spheres. A voice from the heavens echoes "Reset, reduce, turn up, repeat" until the words lose all meaning and are battered into the metal walls by distilled rhythms. Closing track â€Worlds Falling Out the Bottomâ€ brings with it a sense of calm and a respite for the next chapter. 
EP2 is the last ashes of a manuscript that's been waiting for ages to be turned into dust. It is the final nail in the coffin of his past that began with EP1 and Lines Describing Circles. 
Peder Mannerfelts music is gradual and always on the move, the process spans over the whole production.

title: It's Never Gonna Be Over For Me

description:
This is the year of Peder Mannerfelt's rebirth.  After seven years he's laid The Subliminal Kid to rest.  With this new 12", the chains have been locked in and the road map has been obliterated.  EP1 is focused like a laser etching out intricate patterns in massive, humming machines.  Mannerfelt's ideas have been reduced to a razor's edge and he balances these freeform compositions like a master.
This EP could be seen as a prelude to Peder Mannerfelt's debut album under his own name that will be released by Digitalis Industries in February and at the same time is the first part in a ongoing series of self released records by Mannerfelt.
Opener "Hook (end)" crashes like waves from a metallic ocean bearing down on the shore.  The bass craters beneath, digging its way to the listener's core.  Each idea is stripped down and simplified to the point of near exhaustion, resulting in tracks that are relentless and infecting.  "Psalms and Songs and Voices" is propelled forward by crushing kick drums and rhythmic bass pounding.  Somehow, though, Mannerfelt works unsuspecting hooks in between the peaks.  It's incredible.  "With Psalms and Songs and Praises," the final track on this 12", everything is pushed to the limit.  This is absolute maximalism; an overload of the senses that cannot be escaped.  It's the opposite of everything else on the EP, combining everything into a single, massive escape.
This is the sound of machines humming.  This is the sound of the factory floor in rebellion.  And yet, this is only the beginning; the first chapter of a novel yet to come.  This is the sound of Peder Mannerfelt finding his voice.

"With Psalms and Songs and Praises," the final track on this 12", everything is pushed to the limit.  This is absolute maximalism; an overload of the senses that cannot be escaped.  It's the opposite of everything else on the EP, combining everything into a single, massive escape.
This is the sound of machines humming.  This is the sound of the factory floor in rebellion.  And yet, this is only the beginning; the first chapter of a novel yet to come.  This is the sound of Peder Mannerfelt finding his voice.
title: Expanding Sineways

description:
This is the year of Peder Mannerfelt's rebirth.  After seven years he's laid The Subliminal Kid to rest.  With this new 12", the chains have been locked in and the road map has been obliterated.  EP1 is focused like a laser etching out intricate patterns in massive, humming machines.  Mannerfelt's ideas have been reduced to a razor's edge and he balances these freeform compositions like a master.
This EP could be seen as a prelude to Peder Mannerfelt's debut album under his own name that will be released by Digitalis Industries in February and at the same time is the first part in a ongoing series of self released records by Mannerfelt.
Opener "Hook (end)" crashes like waves from a metallic ocean bearing down on the shore.  The bass craters beneath, digging its way to the listener's core. description:
After many requests....  here you go.  This is our official rework of the Iza original.  Originally produced as music for a ballet performance by Ballet Philippines and choreographed by Denisa Reyes.  
This was probably the single most popular Philippine pop song of the year, when prefaced with 2 theater actors improvising a scene taken from Rizal's Noli Me Tangere it will either make sense to you or not.  You can skip through the bossa into but the track won't have any impact without the spoken introduction.  
When this was first performed we were very interested in the idea of 3D sound and there is alot of strange phase induced positioning, I don't know if this will translate into an mp3 but if you have a nice setup at home let us know if the bass behind you makes the hair on the back of your neck stand up...  
Noypi!

description:
This tune was written around 2002-3[?]  the tune was made in complete isolation but then we jammed with Karl Roy twice in the studio in improv recordings... and then I harvested from his tracks and dropped a vocal in, it seemed appropriate at the time.  I must find the masters as somewhere we have 2 hours of Karl just doing improv recorded decently. Karl only 'appears' twice in this track but the tune certainly fitted our relationships, our music and our lives.  At once; mellow but longing, melancholy put hopeful, Stupid but fun, intelligent but crass and knowing but innocent.  Travel well brother.

Hence thank you Karl for the music, the performances, the collaborations, the offer of a lift home (that I made to you in 95), the make up, the flavors, the spice.  May your journey continue on the path that you shared with us;  a very open mind and a big middle finger close behind. Punk IS dead, it had to die to get funky; but only you'll get that. PLUR.

Millions of listeners all over the world enjoy the mesmerising music of the Persian artist Bahramji, who calls Ibiza home.
Long before Berlin based producer Chris Zippel moved to the island and became friends with the musician, Bahram's Chill Out Albums â€œSufi Safirâ€ and â€œSufiyanâ€ in collaboration with the artist Mashti had a huge impact on him. 
Their co-creation on the track SANDS features Bahrams unique way of singing and playing his trademark 72-string instrument, the Santur;

Combined with the productions skills of veteran producer Chris the track comes in a tempo of 113 Bpm in different mixes and dub versions.

May all beings be happy and at peace!

description:
This is the final chapter of the Petrichor / Hiraeth series "REMIXED" featuring artists like Riccicomoto, Aiora, STR3E & Chris Zippel.


Riccicomoto 
is an Ibiza based producer with his own radio show on Ibiza Global Radio. He is known for his atmospheric dub techno and cineastic
sound, preparing an album release on his own now on Big AlÂ´s â€œReady Mix Recordsâ€ this summer.

STR3E
The classically trained SaÃ¯d Daghelfi aka STR3E  (pronounced S3)
is an artist from the north of France. After playing for many years live in various nu-jazz & electronic bands in Lille & Paris, 
he started the downtempo project IÃ‹LO with many quality releases in all its sub genres. STR3E reflects his love for modern moody electronica.

Ariora
The greek artist Aiora has released on labels like PFL, Existence and Timewarp as well as on Ritchie Hawtins Minus Records after winning a remix competition for one of Hawtins songs.
Besides his musical career the Crete born music producer is running the stylish cocktail bar Kolokotroni 9 in Athens, hosting live Dj sets every other day. 
For his interpretation of Hiraeth he explores the darker vibes of his techno universe combined with african drum sounds.

Chris Zippel
aka CRSZPL is an electronic veteran music producer from Berlin who has worked with an impressive variety of well-known artists, including Pet Shop Boys, Klaus Schulze, Jose Padilla, Norah Jones, SNAP, Steve Lawler, Marmion, Namito and Vincent Littlehat.
His remix starts with a deephouse vibe, introducing later a reprogramming of a famous 90s acid bassline.

description:
Now on bandcamp:
http://genuinesounds.bandcamp.com/album/still-love-ep


Chris Zippel counts among the most prolific ambient/downtempo artists of the present timeâ€¦ production work with Artists like the Pet Shop Boys, Robbie Williams, Ich und Ich, Snap and just lately Jose Padilla (with whom he just finished on top two remixes for the american Singer Norah Jones), speaks volumes.

His latest original single effort "Still Love", featuring the stand out voice of scandinavian songstress Sophie Tusnelda, creates a deep, unique vibe fuelled by the genuine Zippel trademark sound of course. "Sophie writes those kind of lyrics that come very close to my imagination of perfect melancholy" Chris says - and puts on smile.  

The silky original version of "Still Love" comes alongside three tantalizing remixes on this debut EP for Mole Listening Pearls.  
The Klangstein & Chris Zippel mix adds quite a vital dose of bass heavy downtempo groove to the sensual original - meanwhile, both the Aiora In Dub mix as well as the Chris Zippel & Dimitris Giakoumakis mix aim clearly at the adult dancefloors around the globe.
All that a tasty precursor to the upcoming Chris Zippel album... which incorporates an intense amount of inspiration that the vivid producer has soaked up in & around his new homebase, the white island of Ibiza, throughout the course of the last three years.

Just like on ChrisÂ´s' previous Album, the refined cover artwork was created by Yoram Roth Photography.

title: Chris Zippel feat Sophie Tusnelda - Still Love  (4 Mixes Snippet/ Demo)

description:
JEN meets CHIN CHILLAZ - No Ordinary Life 
(soon out on stereo deluxe records)

With â€žNo Ordinary Lifeâ€œ, Washington based love poet JEN revisits her tantalizing 2008 debut album â€žMellow Dramasâ€œ once more... alongside infamous dubbernauts CHIN CHILLAZ (aka George Solar & Fe Wolter) that is. The dreamy, string-loaden original track gets the remix treatment in three deep updates this time around. 

First up is Ibiza based CHRIS ZIPPEL (aka GENUINE SOUNDS), a household name not only in the electronic and ambient world but also because of his sensual production work for a.o. THE PET SHOP BOYS, ROBBIE WILLIAMS and german mega pop act ICH & ICH. The GENUINE SOUNDS remix of â€žNo Ordinary Lifeâ€œ teleports the slow motion original straight onto the adult dub disco dancefloor with a wide smile... balearic for real!

Cologne based producer duo RUBBASOL, on the downtempo scene since the mid nineties and as of late active with providing trademark sound remixes for a.o. MASSIVAN and Budapest lounge dons GELKA (courtesy of the NIGHTMARES ON WAX imprint WAX ON Reords), provide a pretty hypnotic headnodder fueled by an analog synth pattern frenzy... and the inevitable echo chamber of course.   

Meanwhile, Auckland/New Zealand based dj/sound activist MORNING STEPPA has prepared an intriguingly positive post-dubstep chassis for JENâ€™s one-in-a-million voice and poetry to travel in safely.... even in southern hemispheres. 

In an ordinary world, this is definitely no ordinary remix package!

description:
For RE:WARM 006 we present a collection of music from one of San Francisco's best kept secrets, Dr Robert Blackman. "The Unimaginable DreamWorks" is a collection of five tracks from three musical masterpieces he put out between 1983-1985 on his own Riverwinds imprint.

A practising chiropractor by day with his own holistic health centre in San Francisco, these songs became his love, passion and focus. Together with Michael Pluznick, a very accomplished percussionist they painstakingly put together an ensemble of musicians to bring the tracks to life. The melting pot for this body of work was Hyde Street Studios which still today is based in deepest San Francisco and has seen names such as Neil Young, Earth Wind & Fire and John Waters to name a few grace its studio space.

Singers and musicians alike came together from all over the world to bring Robertâ€™s vision to reality. This included an Australian didgeridoo player, an electric violin and piano player from Paraguay as well as singers and a choir from the surrounding local churches.

Together through Dr Robert Blackman's eyes they created a fabulous sound of twisted disco punk funk like no other that still sounds relevant today as it did back in the eighties. The energy and the stories are clear to hear throughout the five tracks which make up "The Unimaginable DreamWorksâ€ of Dr. Robert Blackman 1983-1985.

Artwork was key to the releases and the â€œPeace Is Aliveâ€ painting incorporated on the label of the release appeared in TIME magazine in 1984 when Dr Robert Blackman was treating combat vets, suffering from PTSD and this was the name of the job fair for veterans he set up.

To promote the album at the time Dr Robert Blackman flew up over San Francisco in a single engine prop airplane loaded with 50,000 leaflets. Strapped in at 500 feet the leaflets were dropped on the city of San Francisco! The following day, the media descended on his holistic health centre, called Riverwinds and in turn he was fined $1,000 for the cleanup!

Dr Robert Blackman's "The Unimaginable DreamWorks" is out on Friday May 28th both digitally and physically.

description:
For RE:WARM 005 we present a slice of obscure, relatively under the radar gospel from Winston Neale that we discovered back in 2019 via his Flying High, private press L.P from 1986.

Winston Neale first learnt to sing gospel standards as a child via his mother the late Eloise Neale and went on to sing with the Bethel Gospel Church from the age of 6. Winston always had an ambition to release a gospel album and on relocating to Canada this became a reality. The Flying High L.P was the culmination of all he had learnt as a gospel singer, covering songs by Robert and Joyce Irvine & Rev. E.A. Hoffman / A.J Showalter amongst others on this record. The song we became most interested in was the "Sinnerman" track written by Winston and his wife, Susan, a haunting yet beautifully atmospheric slice of new gospel. Winstonâ€™s voice, taut hand drums, guitar, bass and flute all make this an essential piece of soulful gospel with a really distinct tropical feel.

To complete the project, we assigned remix duties to one of our favourite producer duos, Quiet Village. In Joel and Matt's own words they "loved the vibe of the original song, something the Japanese would label as 'free-soul' but with a beautiful floaty island feel like Jon Lucien." Utilising the powerful accapella, they decided to go down a more experimental path, to deconstruct the track using dub techniques for a modern 'Black Ark' style Quiet Village redux.

The package comes complete with remastered audio and new accompanying artwork paying homage to the original "Flying High" album cover.

RE:WARM 005 will be out physically and digitally on Friday March 19th.

Pre-order the 12" here >

Winstonâ€™s voice, taut hand drums, guitar, bass and flute all make this an essential piece of soulful gospel with a really distinct tropical feel.

To complete the project, we assigned remix duties to one of our favourite producer duos, Quiet Village. In Joel and Matt's own words they "loved the vibe of the original song, something the Japanese would label as 'free-soul' but with a beautiful floaty island feel like Jon Lucien." Utilising the powerful accapella, they decided to go down a more experimental path, to deconstruct the track using dub techniques for a modern 'Black Ark' style Quiet Village redux.

The package comes complete with remastered audio and new accompanying artwork paying homage to the original "Flying High" album cover.

RE:WARM 005 will be out physically and digitally on Friday March 19th.

title: B1 > Winston Neale - Sinnerman (Quiet Village Remix)

description:
For RE:WARM 005 we present a slice of obscure, relatively under the radar gospel from Winston Neale that we discovered back in 2019 via his Flying High, private press L.P from 1986.

Winston Neale first learnt to sing gospel standards as a child via his mother the late Eloise Neale and went on to sing with the Bethel Gospel Church from the age of 6. Winston always had an ambition to release a gospel album and on relocating to Canada this became a reality. The Flying High L.P was the culmination of all he had learnt as a gospel singer, covering songs by Robert and Joyce Irvine & Rev. E.A. Hoffman / A.J Showalter amongst others on this record. description:
For RE:WARM 002 we head back to 1992 and over to San Francisco to bring you a timeless house record by Daisy Glow.

Daisy Glow is the collaboration between San Francisco house producers Mouse & Kelix Williams who formed as a spin-off from their live act Tasti Box. Their Daisy Glow guise which previously came out on ZoÃ«Magik Records gave them the chance to make music inspired by full moon raves on the beach and Sunday afternoon raves in Golden Gate Park. In essence a musical reflection of the vibe and sound of San Francisco in the early 90â€™s. From these sessions came the Give It All EP. Over the last couple of years the EP has made itâ€™s way back into a number of DJâ€™s record bags and was previously supported by the likes of Sasha and John Digweed back in the 90â€™s.

Sounding as relevant now as it did in 1992 the three tracks that comprise the EP sit easily in any house set to this day with their old school house sound. Each track having its own identity and all three being house music of the highest order.

description:
RE:WARM 001 // RECORD STORE DAY RELEASE
A: Dalvanius & The Fascinations â€“ Voodoo Lady 
AA: Golden Harvest â€“ I Need Your Love
*Ltd to 500*

Over the past eighteen monthsâ€™ Warmâ€™s Ali Tillett and Micky Browne have been discussing records and sharing insights into each otherâ€™s record collections. Off the back of this RE:WARM is born as an outlet to showcase music from both their collections that they felt deserved to be revisited and shared with the world as a lot of it had previously been overlooked or worse still, undiscovered. 

Both having collected records for twenty years or more, their influences and ever-growing collections range from Folk, Jazz, Soul, AOR, Disco, Funk, House, Balearic and much more in between. So over the months and years to come expect every musical stone to be unturned on their quest to reintroduce friends, Peers and contemporaries to some of their favourite over looked gems, all lovingly repackaged and presented with stunning new art work and original photos. 

For their inaugural release to launch the RE:WARM label on record store day 2020 they have gone all the way to the Southern Hemisphere for a New Zealand double header. 

First up on the A side is Dalvanius & The Fascinations phenomenal track, Voodoo Lady. On first release this track started life as the B-side of the lead track â€œCheckmate on Loveâ€ but later moved to the A side with a slightly longer Disco Version. This version is more recently starting to appear in collectors want lists and on auction sites around the world. 

On the flip is Golden Harvest with their AOR-Disco anthem, I Need Your Love. One of those tracks for premium dancefloor moments of joy and hands in the air excitement. This one started life on the independent N.Z label Impact in 1977 and later in 1978 got the Warner Bros treatment for Neighbouring Australia and was later to be included on their only album Golden Harvest â€“ Golden Harvest. 

RE:WARM 001 is out on Record Store Day // Saturday April 18th on 7â€ // www.recordstoreday.co.uk

For all enquiries please contact Micky @ Warm // micky@warmagency.com

description:
As part of a new mix series, the Warm residents will be delving into their favourite record labels from the past and present. Up first Mr Warm himself, Ali Tillett steps up with one of his favourite labels from the past. As you can imagine with all the labels we will be choosing there are quite a few records to choose from, from their back catalogues but we hope the mixes will give you a sprinkling of why we love them so much and will get you digging into the labels catalogues' more!

For our inaugural label mix we head to Sheffield to showcase Toko Records which was set up up in 1994 by Paul Ingall and Alec Greenhough (aka Toko Productions). PREMIERE : LOR - White Light (Original Mix) [Warm]

About Warm 003 : LOR - Mystery To The Viewer EP

Warm return once againâ€¦ One of the most consistent and influential agencies to have operated in the 2000s, the collective continue to develop their original agency, events and record label, and things are heating up very nicely. Following soul-arresting releases from Elliott Lion and Face + Heel comes this four-track odyssey from Belfastâ€™s Lunar Orbit Rendezvous AKA LOR. Ready for take-off?

Our mission is set with â€˜Mystery To The Viewerâ€™, but what is the main mystery? Is it the gravity-defying thrust of our engines or the identity of the anonymous (yet well spoken) narrator? Listen closely for clues amid the heavy pulsating chords as we break away from the earth orbit and plunge deeper into the stars.

â€˜In This Detailâ€™ sees us hurtling further and further into the dark unknown. Thereâ€™s a deep chilling aesthetic at play here as LOR makes his 808s weep with the loneliness only a long-stay astronaut can sympathise with. In perfect contrast, the isolation is balanced by the direct and vital â€˜Orioleâ€™. One of LORâ€™s earliest projects, updated with all the skills and techniques heâ€™s learnt on labels such as Exit Strategy and Cin Cin, itâ€™s a vital composition that rises and rises as we engage hyperspeed through the cosmos. 

Finally we land back on our home planet to the marching momentum of â€˜White Lightâ€™. Almost stately in its pace and rhythmic stride, things suddenly take a turn for the intense as a warping bass siren triggers a much darker direction and a series of spasmodic kicks and heavily shelved filters. Welcome homeâ€¦

@lor_belfast
@warmhq

description:
After a brief hiatus the podcast series is back and we are very happy to hand the controls over to Mark E. Having returned to the agency roster last month we are very excited to be working with him again as he's currently in the studio finalising a whole heap of new music for release this year so keep those eyes and ears peeled! In the meantime dive into this new mix he has put together for your listening pleasure x

The Wolverhampton-reared, DJ/producer has had a slow, steady ascension to his status as one of the genre's most natural talents. Mark E's love affair with electronic dance music began early, as an adolescent, when rave culture swept through England. Diving headfirst into the surprisingly fertile Wolverhampton scene, tasting house at the hands of legends like John Kelly and Frankie Knuckles before a move to Birmingham for University also installed him in a larger club scene.

Mark's first forays into production were, naturally, edits-warm, understated, and interestingly mellow, with tempos hovering somewhere between 105 and 115 BPM. (Or thereabouts.) Once "Scared," a ten-minute rework of Womack & Womack's "Baby, I'm Scared Of You," found the ears of influential selector (and, more importantly, BBC radio DJ) Giles Peterson, it was on, and a solid string of memorable, vinyl-only releases introduced the world at large to this humble, devoted househead. Mark went beyond edits and into original production, releasing with labels like Running Back, Golf Channel, ESP & Futureboogie, plus starting his own label, MERC, and honing a sound that was uniquely blue collar and utilitarian-classic, almost industrial house, with a tinge of disco warmth.

A stellar remix for Matthew Dear's "Little People (Black City)" introduced him to the Ghostly/Spectral fold, releasing his first two albums, which proved to be as defining as anything he's done, a symbol of his unique spot in the global club music landscape, sounding simultaneously familiar and unique like few others can.

description:
Multi-faceted Irish musician David Kitt aka New Jackson returns to Permanent Vacation in full force, riding high from releasing his critically acclaimed debut album "From Night To Night", which was filled with rich melodies, dusty synth pop, late-night boogie and cinematic deep house. For his third PV EP, New Jackson tightens the strings and brings back the bounce with two rather floor-friendly tracks that are still deeply rooted in the unique New Jackson universe. To round things up "Feather By Feather" is a love-trenched early morning anthem, which is the perfect soundtrack for doing all things that are nice in this world.

description:
Full album available to download on Bandcamp. Follow the track's download link. 

These collected recordings are exports from a generative composition performed at Acud Macht Neu in Berlin in January 2018. The application that drives the music is being developed as part of a larger research project into creative opportunities within crystallography. What you hear is generated by a model for describing incommensurate structures in crystallography. 

Conventional crystalline materials are those in which the component atoms/molecules are arranged with long range translational order in three dimensions: the entire material is constructed from a well-defined structural unit that replicates in three-dimensional space. They have three translational periodicities. For some materials, on the other hand, the arrangement of the component atoms in three-dimensional space can be described only by invoking four or more translational periodicities. Such materials are described as â€œincommensurateâ€. Although existing in three-dimensional physical space, the material is now no longer periodic in three dimensions but is periodic in four or higher dimensions. As such its appearance is not that of a conventional, ordered crystalline material. The three-dimensional structure of the incommensurate material represents a three-dimensional slice through a higher dimensional superspace. 

The idea of an incommensurate material can be represented by creating a series of sine waves, arranged in a periodic fashion in two dimensions with the start point of each sine wave offset along a diagonal. This represents a two-dimensional structure. Drawing a line through the set of sine waves creates a one-dimensional slice through the two-dimensional structure. The points of intersection of the line and the sine wave will be incommensurate and the values of the distance between them will never be found to repeat exactly. 

To use this model of describing incommensurate structures to make music, the data output of a mathematical algorithm is used to drive an aleatoric composition written in Cycling74â€™s Max. Changes in variables input to the algorithm result in changes to the data. These in turn transform the work through the creation of new scales, generated from intervals present in the data. These intervals are also used to govern other musical variables within the work; time and pitch structures for example. The final work exists as a set of instructions generating an endless piece of music. 

More information on this project will be posted here: 
composingwithcrystallography.tumblr.com
